</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-gvZzpm chTUkt pf-55_ pf-heading-1-h3"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-57_">Cotton Farming and Pesticide Use
</span></h2><p class="sc-bfhwqR jqvVoJ pf-58_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-60_"><strong><a href="https://www.ellenmacarthurfoundation.org/a-new-textiles-economy" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);"></span></a></strong>The cultivation of <strong>conventional cotton</strong>, a primary material for fast fashion, uses large amounts of <strong>pesticides and fertilizers that contaminate the soil and water</strong>, affecting local ecosystems [5]. Pollinators like bees and butterflies, which are vital for food production, suffer dramatically in cotton-growing areas. In regions such as India and the United States, <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3298/11/8/182" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);"><strong>pesticide use has led to a 40% decrease in pollinator populations</strong></span></a> [6,7].








 







