</span></h2><p class="sc-bfhwqR jqvVoJ pf-99_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-101_">The textile dyeing process is another major source of environmental damage. Toxic chemicals such as lead and cadmium are used in dyes, and when discharged into rivers in countries like <strong>India, Bangladesh, </strong>and <strong>China, they poison fish and amphibians</strong> [11,12]. For instance, the<strong> Citarum River </strong>in Indonesia has <strong>lost 60% of its fish species</strong> due to the toxic runoff from textile factories [13,14], while in Bangladesh, amphibians near textile factories show <strong><a href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Shuchismita-Dey/publication/283507015_A_Review_on_Textile_Wastewater_Characterization_in_Bangladesh/links/5f981e52458515b7cfa1996f/A-Review-on-Textile-Wastewater-Characterization-in-Bangladesh.pdf" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);">genetic mutations caused by chemical exposure</span></a></strong> [15].














 










